{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:18:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2355"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2355"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.81,0.04,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42474"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to his GP explaining he is worried about his memory. He reports he has been \u0022completely and hopelessly forgetful\u0022 for the past four months and is worried that he might be developing Alzheimer\u2019s dementia, like his grandfather. Over the past four months he has developed significant fatigue and feels sad and moody. He has taken leave from his job due to poor concentration and thought he might start a new business instead, but has been sleeping throughout the day. He has also lost 6kg in the last month.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis parents died in a road accident when he was a 4-year-old and he was cared for by his grandparents.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has poor self care. His vital signs are within normal limits. He speaks slowly and takes long pauses between sentences. He has no tremor or rigidity but walks slowly. He has no papilloedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his forgetfulness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alzheimer\u2019s dementia","Parkinson\u2019s disease","Major depressive disorder","Brain tumour","Frontotemporal dementia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient fulfils the criteria for DSM-V \u003Cstrong\u003Emajor depressive disorder (MDD)\u003C/strong\u003E. The criteria can be memorised with the mnemonic \u003Cstrong\u003EDIGSPACES:\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED\u003C/strong\u003Eepressed/sad mood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI\u003C/strong\u003Enterest - low/decreased\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EG\u003C/strong\u003Euilt\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Eleep disturbance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EP\u003C/strong\u003Esychomotor retardation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA\u003C/strong\u003Eppetite changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC\u003C/strong\u003Eoncentration - impaired\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Energy - low \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Euicidal ideation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo be diagnosed with MDD, the patient must have at least 5 of the above symptoms (and at least one must be either sad mood or decreased interest) for \u22652 weeks. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMDD is associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Ereversible\u003C/strong\u003E dementia called \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudodementia\u003C/strong\u003E or dementia of major depressive disorder. Patients with pseudodementia present with features of depression along with impaired concentration and increasing forgetfulness. It is a clinical diagnosis. Pseudodementia is reversible and can be treated by managing the underlying major depressive disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlzheimer\u2019s disease is unlikely to present with major depressive disorder symptoms. Patients may also have agnosia and severe decline in other cognitive domains impacting their ability to function independently. In addition, patients with Alzheimer\u2019s dementia are unlikely to be bothered by their memory impairment and are usually brought to the doctor by their family members.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParkinson\u2019s dementia may have associated Parkinsons\u0027 motor features;  bradykinesia, rigidity, and tremor. They may also have a Dementia with Lewy Bodies (DLB) type syndrome involving visual hallucinations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrontotemporal dementia typically presents with early personality changes including disinhibition and apathy. Late changes involve memory impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBrain tumour is unlikely given he has no headaches, no visual disturbances, no focal neurological deficits and no symptoms of raised intracranial pressure. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A major depressive disorder is an important cause of forgetfulness."],"references":["Tobe E. Pseudodementia caused by severe depression. Case Reports. 2012;2012(dec14 1):bcr2012007156-bcr2012007156.","Brodaty H, Connors M. Pseudodementia, pseudo\u2010pseudodementia, and pseudodepression. Alzheimer\u0027s \u0026 Dementia: Diagnosis, Assessment \u0026 Disease Monitoring. 2020;12(1)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2355"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-22T09:49:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T14:47:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29251"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam